description.plain:
Destin Choice Route (b. October 31, 1990), better known by the stage name J.I.D, is an American rapper from Zone 6, Atlanta, Georgia. He describes himself as “a soft-spoken but intricate lyricist with a cocky side.” His stage name originates from “jittery,” his grandmother’s nickname for him due to his sporadic behavior as a child.

J.I.D began attending Hampton University on a football scholarship in the fall of 2008. At that time, he was nicknamed ‘Jidd’ and released music under multiple variations of that name. His first mixtape, CakeWalk, was released in May 2010 and featured a number of friends from Hampton. The tape also marked two of his earliest collaborations with EARTHGANG. He released his second mixtape, CakeWalk 2, in June 2011. J.I.D was expelled from Hampton at some point during his senior year. Route of Evil was released in June 2012 as J.I.D’s third mixtape. DJ Tay James, Justin Bieber’s official DJ, hosted each of these three mixtapes. J.I.D does not publicly acknowledge any of these tapes, and they are not easily discoverable on the internet.

In October 2013, J.I.D released Para Tu, his fourth mixtape. Around this time, he also officially created the Spillage Village collective with EARTHGANG, Hollywood JB, and JordxnBryant. J.I.D re-released Para Tu on SoundCloud in December 2017 after fans had discovered it and were posting it online.

In February 2014, J.I.D and the rest of Spillage Village released Bears Like This, their first compilation. In July of that year, J.I.D released Lucky Buddha, a collaborative EP with Money Makin' Nique.

In January 2015, J.I.D released DiCaprio, an EP that ignited his rise to fame. Later that year, in July, Spillage Village released Bears Like This Too, their second compilation. In November 2015, J.I.D was an opening act on Omen’s Elephant Eyes Tour.

In December 2016, Spillage Village released Bears Like This Too Much, their third compilation and the conclusion of the Bears Like This series. The album notably featured J. Cole and Bas.

J.I.D signed to J. Cole’s Dreamville Records on February 20, 2017. Less than three weeks after his signing, he released his debut studio album, The Never Story, on March 10, 2017.

On November 26, 2018, J.I.D released DiCaprio 2, his sophomore studio album, which is also a sequel to his 2015 EP.

Also, in late November 2018, his stage name was adjusted to JID (without the periods) on streaming services in order to make it easier for users to find his music.

songs.title: 151 Rum

description.plain:
“151 Rum” is the lead single from DiCaprio 2. It is J.I.D’s first solo release since his June 2017 single, “Hasta Luego.”

J.I.D announced the song, its single artwork, and its release date on Instagram on September 16, 2018. In the caption of the post, J.I.D wrote a heartfelt message to his fans.

“151 Rum” is named after Bacardi 151, a discontinued brand of highly alcoholic rum, which is itself named after its alcohol proof level of 151. Bacardi 151 was sold in the US from 1963 to 2016; its production was then discontinued indefinitely.

In an Instagram live video on the day of the song’s release, J.I.D gave an in-depth discussion on the song’s meaning and background.

songs.title: NEVER

description.plain:
On the lead single from his debut studio album, J.I.D reflects on difficult times in his life in which he did not amount to anything and had very little to his name. Despite his hardships, however, he never felt sorry for himself and always worked hard to achieve what he desired.

This song was first released on February 10, 2016, but it gained more notoriety upon J.I.D’s signing to J. Cole’s Dreamville Records.

songs.title: Off da Zoinkys

description.plain:
On this anti-drug anthem, J.I.D raps about how narcotics have negatively affected him, his environment, and the rap game. He pledges to get “Off da Zoinkys,” and he pleads for others to do the same because he knows the damage that drugs can cause.

The song’s theme of combatting drug abuse is similar to that of J. Cole’s KOD.

songs.title: Slick Talk

description.plain:
J.I.D wanted to make a bold statement for the album’s first song. On this track, he delivers a lot of “Slick Talk” to his fellow rappers, explicitly stating his superiority to them. He warns them that his rise to the top of the rap game is undoubtedly imminent, and he challenges his peers to prove him wrong. Because of the trials and tribulations he has experienced in his life, J.I.D has no reason to suppress himself or sugarcoat his intentions.

This song perfectly sets the tone for the rest of the album as J.I.D continues to challenge his competition and showcase his artistic abilities throughout.

songs.full_title: Surround Sound by JID (Ft. 21 Savage & Baby Tate)
songs.title: Surround Sound

description.plain:
“Surround Sound” is the first collaboration between Atlanta artists J.I.D, 21 Savage, and Baby Tate. It was first teased as a song between J.I.D and DJ Scheme in a tweet on April 5, 2020.

On September 20, 2021, Barry Johnson, one of J.I.D’s managers, teased the song’s imminent release when he posted a short clip of J.I.D and Savage from the filming of the music video.

On January 10, 2022, J.I.D officially announced the song’s new title and release date.

The first version of this song leaked in late-August 2021 with the title “Houses.” In November 2021, the official version leaked.

songs.title: D/vision

description.plain:
“D/vision” is the fifth track off of J.I.D’s debut studio album, The Never Story.

This J. Cole-produced track features fellow Dreamville Records-duo EARTHGANG (Doctur Dot and Johnny Venus)—who, together with J.I.D, are members of Spillage Village. The Spillage Village emcees nonchalantly show off their lyrical ingenuity in “D/vision.”

For the official video for “D/vision,” click here.

songs.full_title: Skrawberries by JID (Ft. BJ the Chicago Kid)
songs.title: Skrawberries

description.plain:
On this sugary song “for da ladies,” J.I.D raps about his significant other and the struggles they are having in their relationship. Despite the mistakes they have both made, they will always be there for each other. Their mutual love is reassured by BJ the Chicago Kid’s chorus. J.I.D also raps about women empowerment, specifically talking about important females in his life.

The late Mac Miller assisted with curation on “Skrawberries,” while the song’s production was handled by J. Cole, Masego, and Ron Gilmore.

songs.title: LAUDER

description.plain: “LAUDER,” the final, J. Cole produced track on The Never Story finds J.I.D opening up about his past, his dreams of going big in the rap industry, and what he believes he was born to accomplish. He also reflects on his reckless and often self destructive behavior, often directly contradicting his more benevolent lines with equally violent ones.

songs.title: Hereditary

description.plain:
Hereditary is a song that explains J.I.D.’s experience with a girl who’s been around nothing but infidelity growing up. He wants to build a relationship with her, but he gets cheated on and realizes that it’s all she knows.
He wants the best for her and wants the relationship to work, but she is quick to manipulate him and take him for granted.

songs.title: Kody Blu 31

description.plain:
Kody Blu 31 is song dedicated to JID’s friend son named Kody. Kody was football player and his number was 31.  Sadly, Kody died at a young age. Song is about JID trying to help Kody’s family to ‘'keep swanging on’‘ or to keep her head high, keep living life. JID mentioned this song back in 2021 in now deleted tweet.

songs.title: Crack Sandwich

description.plain:
“Crack Sandwich” sees JID tell a story that illustrates the dynamic between himself and his six siblings. Over the course of the song, the Atlanta native demonstrates his trademark abilities when creating wordplay in his music. JID recounts an experience where he and his siblings ignited an all-out brawl in the streets of New Orleans while recordings of his family discussing the aftermath segment the track’s verses. The chorus paints the Route family’s parents as harsh, yet, by the end of the song, JID thinks his parents would appreciate the bond created by their children once they began throwing hands with customers at the New Orleans bar. Their love for one another derives from their impulsiveness, he compares his brothers and sisters to crackheads, made even more comedically poetic when they end up in a paddy wagon by the end of the song. A “crack sandwich,” is an illusionary device representing how each member of his family contributes to disorganized and rambunctious concoction. When told by his parents during the hook to go “make a sandwich” in favor of paying for a cheeseburger, JID instead makes due with his siblings' inventiveness, choosing to appreciate his familiar relationships akin to creating a metaphorical crack sandwich.

Nearly a year before its release, over half of the track was previewed during JID’s live perfomance for Vans Sidestripe Session. Two months before that, on May 29, 2021, he revealed the track’s title, declaring it the hardest song on the album to write.

songs.title: All Bad

description.plain: The seventh track from J.I.D’s 2017 album The Never Story. In the track, J.I.D is finally telling his girl the truth, that he is all bad. The soft vocals provided by Philadelphia singer/songwriter Mereba and the instrumental together form an emotional track with a message about truth in love. It is portrayed to be a confession between two lovers.

songs.title: Sistanem

description.plain:
JID dedicates a full song to his sister, who is one of the most influential and important people to him, as he once expressed in a tweet.

The three verses run chronologically, and details how their relationship has evolved from when he was younger, to the recent days of fame.

This song follows ‘’Bruddanem‘’, a song themed around the importance of brotherhood, thus developing a two-song run under a similar kinship motif. songs.title: General

description.plain:
In “General,” J.I.D officially introduces himself to the public as Atlanta’s latest up and coming rapper. Here he tells his story of playing college football until he got kicked out of college.

He also reflects on his past decisions during this incident and how they affected his future. Lyrics like

Glad we did that, now I’m flying to Los Angeles with a 8th in my pre-rolls,

express his newfound gratitude for getting kicked out, as if he hadn’t been he wouldn’t have turned to rapping.

This song serves as J.I.D’s opportunity to push his talent forward to the public by sharing his story,  and how he can compete with other rappers by utilizing his impressive flows and clever rhyme schemes.

He also states his opinion on trap rappers, as Atlanta is known for artists such as Gucci Mane and Future.

description.plain:
To conclude one of the most acclaimed albums of the year; JID presents a proper storytelling in “2007,” that connects the listener to know a little more about the rise and hard work that the rapper had to do, along with his past memories and the inspiration that led to having the career he has today.

On the 7-minute song, JID tells about his journey going back to 2007, when one of his idols' career began with his debut mixtape—which is J. Cole—he explains what his life was like while he was in school, playing with friends and sharing his experiences, as well as meeting various people along the way, such as EARTHGANG and more — He digs a little deeper into the passing of the years, it is given an untimely change due to unexpected events that Destin had and how his life largely declined before being what it is now.

Also, the song features additional vocals from the current Dreamville president, Ibrahim “Ib” Hamad, which talks about the effort of making a song and how difficult it is to make a good one; His father Carl Route Jr., which expresses his pride in where his son was currently and the memory he had as a child; and lastly, from his mentor J. Cole, who talks more about how he met JID during an EARTHGANG event and how he was signed to Dreamville in 2017.

The song was going to be released along with the release of The Forever Story, but due to clearance issues it couldn’t appear to avoid problems; Although, it was released for a few days on the official Dreamville channel on JID’s father’s birthday. It would not be until November 2, that JID would confirm the official release of the song along with an extension of the album, released the next day.

songs.title: Bruuuh

description.plain:
Bruuuh is a soundcloud single by J.I.D released on the 11th of January in 2017. The production is handled by Willie B, who has also worked with others like Kendrick Lamar and Wale. In the song J.I.D reflects on feeling underrated and unappriciated, and wanting more, being a lesser known face in the game at the time. he also speaks about his past and upbringing (J.I.D was raised in Atlanta, and wanted to pursue a career in sports).
In the fastest part of the song he hits 7.5 syllables per second, all while he flows incredibly smooth.

songs.title: Stars

description.plain:
“Stars” marks the first collaboration between JID and Yasiin Bey, though both have been fans of eachother for a while. In a 2017 interview on HOT97, Yasiin says

I’m not sitting here… I’m not listening to all these niggas. Why? I could just listen to already made niggas, the shit that gets better with time, and if some new niggas come through, like my man J.I.D from Dreamville. Fire.

Before the release of the Forever story, JID tweeted;

The contrast of sampling ms. Fat booty by mos def to actually having Yasiin Bey on the same album is insane to me

JID sampled Mos Def’s “Ms. Fat Booty” on track 6 of The Forever Story, Surround Sound

In “Stars” JID raps about the start of his rap career and trying to “make it as an artist”.

songs.title: Despacito Too

description.plain:
“Despacito Too”  is a powerful closer to DiCaprio 2. Over three verses, JID discusses what he plans to accomplish in his career, how he will overcome his hindrances, and how people initially disregarded his desire to become a rapper.

The song’s title is a reference to a popular meme about the hit song “Despacito” in which people have started a running joke demanding a sequel to the song. This song is essentially JID’s response to these demands.

songs.title: Skegee

description.plain:
“Skegee” is JID’s first true offering of 2021, following his three-track streaming debut of three previously heard songs two weeks earlier.

The song, an abbreviation of Tuskegee, speaks on the history of both the city and its historically black university. JID juxtaposes his life to historical events that involved Tuskegee, such as the infamous and inhumane Tuskegee Syphilis Study and JID’s personal experience being recruited to the university.

He also tackles other issues of the African American experience and provides his views on the ongoing mistreatment of black people in the United States. The bridges between each verse contain insightful excerpts from an elderly man who has witnessed the deep history of Tuskegee, and he provides the listener with insight and a sense of empowerment.

JID first announced the song via his Instagram about fifteen hours before its release. It came with a note thanking fans for their patience and explaining that he wanted to shed light on an important event in honor of Black History Month. He also stated that he had traveled to Tuskegee to film the music video.

songs.title: Money

description.plain:
Money is the 13th track off JID’s “The Forever Story”. Throughout the song, he recounts his childhood dreams of fame, while describing the struggles of growing up poor in Atlanta.

In an Instagram post shortly after the release of the album, JID shares some insight into the recording of “Money”, saying;

This was one of my favorite sessions during the process of making this album. We got a bunch of kids together to work with us in the studio on this record I also gotta give a special shout-out to my dawg Zion Luster(not pictured) who was on the spilligion album as well.. thank you guys

Money features a sample from I’d Like to Know You Better by Rasputin’s Strash.

description.plain:
Continuing from the original “Lauder” track, we find a more experienced, more successful, and more introspective JID speaking about his internal struggles of the fame he has finally achieved. This is in contrast to the tracks' precursor where JID would rap about his dream of going big. Now that he’s made it, he questions if this is even enough, while the industry simply demands more out of him.  While he can’t resist his deep need to let his rhymes out of his mind and not leave them void, he wonders if people are really hearing these words for what they mean and not just taking it for pure entertainment.

This track contains many parallels from it’s prequel and serves as a true sequel in both content and ideals.

songs.title: Somebody

description.plain: ‘Somebody’ is the 11th track on JID’s The Never Story Album. The song centers around how JID didn’t really know what to do with himself as a kid but he knew what he wanted. When he was picked up by J.Cole and signed to Dreamville, JID saw result of working hard on your rap game and it inspired him to become a better rapper. To become ‘Somebody’.

songs.title: Cludder

description.plain:
JID suddenly released “Cludder Freestyle” after a few consecutive days of being in the studio. The song was released exclusively on SoundCloud and YouTube.

“Cludder,” an intentional misspelling of “clutter,” dicusses the chaos and confusion in JID’s life. He raps about modern social justice issues and the climate of the rap game while also mentioning various aspects of his upbringing.

The single’s artwork reflects the song’s themes as it depicts a cluttered table in a studio room.

Both rappers speak about their hard lifestyles and what problems they’ve faced before in life and how it has impacted them in their work and music.

songs.title: Ambassel

description.plain:
“Ambassel” is a song by Atlanta rapper JID that was released as part of the Madden NFL 22 Soundtrack. JID raps about his come-up and successes while warning his opposition not to test him.

The title “Ambassel” refers to the Ethiopian district of the same name. It is an Amba, or mountain fortress, relating to JID’s raps about being untouchable.

On February 13, 2021, producer DJ Scheme previewed the track in a deleted Instagram post, revealing the song’s title and asking which other artists fans would like to hear on the song. Scheme later talked about the track on his Twitter account.

“LeStudMuffin” serves as a collaboration between JID, OG Maco and EARTHGANG that appears on JID’s DiCaprio. On the track, the artists boast about their childish behavior, sexual prowess, and thuggish pasts.

The title includes the common slang word “hooligangs”, but with a twist to reference their hood origins, while still incorporating the same “Le” prefix that the rest of the songs use.

songs.title: JIDtranada Freestyle

description.plain:
“JIDtranada,” a collaboration between Atlanta-based JID and producer KAYTRANADA, was hinted at by co-founder/A&R of Since The 80s, Zekiel Nicholson, on Twitter.

The song was then released two days later, and five days after his surprise drop of “Cludder Freestyle”, both exclusively on SoundCloud and YouTube.

JID seems to talk about the social climate similar to that of “Cludder,” where he contrasts paradise with the small perfections/imperfections within himself and today’s culture.

“LeTumbapart1” serves as a collaboration between JID and KEY! that appears on JID’s DiCaprio. On the track, the artists discuss their hood origins and the privileged lifestyles they currently lead.

The title implies that this is a multi-part series and still incorporates the same “Le” prefix that the rest of the songs use.

songs.title: Surround Sound (Demo)

description.plain:
This is the initial leaked version of “Surround Sound” by J.I.D, 21 Savage, and Baby Tate.

In this version, there is a first part that was removed from the single version.

This version’s second part contains all of the major aspects of the official version’s first part. However, there are two major differences. The Aretha Franklin sample is used as the chorus here, and Baby Tate’s bridge appears before Savage’s verse.

Lastly, this version cuts off during the intro of what turned out to be the final part of the official version.

It seems that the song was originally intended to be three parts; this extended version could appear on The Forever Story.

songs.title: LeFluGame

description.plain:
“LeFluGame” serves as a collaboration between JID and Jace that appears on JID’s DiCaprio. On the track, the artists discuss their hood origins and their newfound success in the rap game.

The title references American basketball player Michael James' infamous flu game performance, while still incorporating the same “Le” prefix that the rest of the songs use.

songs.title: Robotics

description.plain:
“Robotics” is a braggadocious track that showcases JID’s classic lyricism. Speaking with Billboard, JID talked about the inspiration for the song:

This song was inspired by my perspective growing up in East Atlanta – Boulder Crest/Flat mills area. A lot of people are aware of my lyricism but I wanted to showcase my ability to frame East Atlanta’s shared experiences in song form.

Many fans thought “Robotics” was the first release from Spillage Village’s Bears Like This Too Much but ended up being a Soundcloud cut.

“Hush (Prelude)” serves as the first interlude on JID’s debut mixtape CakeWalk. On this Leslie Wright exclusive track, she professes her love for a man (likely JID) and wonders aloud if the relationship is one-sided.

This track is the prelude of the sixth track on the mixtape, entitled “Hush.”
